## Component Three: Directed Energy and Neurotechnology

This is the component with the greatest uncertainty because the specific equipment used is classified and the cost of deploying it is not publicly documented. But there are reference points.

The Active Denial System, the US Air Force's directed energy pain-compliance weapon, has a development cost of approximately $120 million and a unit cost estimated at $5 to $10 million per system. Those are vehicle-mounted, large-scale systems. The class of directed energy device capable of targeting a specific individual's genitals from street distance — as Pearson documented in Maryland — would be a miniaturized, portable variant. The miniaturization premium on military hardware is typically two to five times the full-scale cost for the development and early production units.

But we are almost certainly not costing hardware procurement here. The program described in Pearson's documentation is not buying new equipment for this operation. It is deploying equipment from an existing inventory, developed at government expense over years. The marginal cost to the operation is not the capital cost of the technology — which was paid by the US taxpayer's defense budget years ago — but the cost of the operators, maintenance, and logistics.

Directed energy weapon operators at the specialized military/contractor level bill at $200 to $400 per hour. Multiple documented incidents over fourteen months, requiring what appears to be mobile deployment in various DC neighborhoods, Maryland, and adjacent areas: assume a dedicated technical team of three to five specialists at 20 hours per week of active deployment. Over fourteen months: $3.5 million to $7 million in operator costs alone.

Voice-to-skull and behavioral steering technology is even more specialized. DARPA's N3 program, from which the behavioral steering capability likely derives, has a program budget in the hundreds of millions. The operators of such systems — if they exist in operational form — would be among the most expensive specialists in the defense contractor ecosystem. Estimating conservatively: the neurotechnology component, including operators and support infrastructure, adds $2 million to $5 million to the operation's cost.

I want to be clear about the uncertainty here. These numbers could be significantly lower if the equipment is older generation and the operators less specialized, or significantly higher if the technology is cutting-edge and the operators are senior. I am using the low end of what the documented technology class would cost at current contractor rates.

**Directed energy and neurotechnology subtotal: $5.5 million to $12 million.**

