## Component Four: Human Asset Management

Recruiting, briefing, managing, and compensating civilian participants in an operation of this kind requires professional case officers — the intelligence community equivalent of field managers. A CIA or FBI case officer with contractor billing runs $150 to $300 per hour. Managing an operation with multiple civilian assets (the neighbor, Ms. Sherry's information channel, the upstairs apartment operative, the street theater network) and multiple technical systems requires at minimum two to three case officers working part-time on the operation.

At three case officers at 15 hours per week each, over fourteen months, at $200 per hour average billing: $1.5 million.

This does not include the recruitment costs — the intelligence officer hours required to identify, approach, vet, and brief civilian participants, which can be the most expensive part of an asset management operation. Add $200,000 to $400,000 for recruitment and initial operational briefings.

There is also the cost of whatever was introduced into Pearson's food or drink during the summer 2025 behavioral episode — the substance or technology that produced a state in which he found himself compelled to write scripture on containers and deliver them to churches. If this was a chemical substance, the cost of producing and deploying it is small compared to the other line items but non-trivial. If it was a technological induction, it falls under the neurotechnology component. Either way, someone planned and executed an operation to introduce something into what Pearson consumed. That required surveillance, access, and execution — all of which have costs already counted in other components.

**Human asset management subtotal: $1.7 million to $1.9 million.**

