## What $16 Million Means

Sixteen million dollars is a significant operational commitment. It is not, however, implausible for an intelligence-community program targeting a specific individual over fourteen months with multiple simultaneous capability streams. The FBI's operation against Martin Luther King Jr. — technologically primitive by comparison, involving no directed energy weapons, no voice-to-skull, and no behavioral steering — has been estimated in today's dollars at $7 to $12 million over seven years. A seven-year operation at $1 to $1.7 million per year. The Pearson operation, at $16 million over fourteen months, is roughly ten times as expensive per unit time. That multiple tracks with the technological upgrade: the equipment costs of 21st-century neurotechnology are not 1960s wiretap costs.

For comparison: $16 million is approximately the annual budget of a mid-sized FBI field office. It is approximately what the federal government spends on a single Homeland Security grant to a major city police department. It is a rounding error in the intelligence community's classified budget, which is estimated at over $90 billion annually. It is the kind of number that can be buried in a program's operational account without any individual line item drawing scrutiny.

This is important. The cost of what Pearson documented is large enough to be operationally significant and small enough to be institutionally invisible. It is precisely in the range where sustained, sophisticated covert operations against domestic targets have historically been funded: expensive enough to be professional, cheap enough to be deniable.

---

## What the Cost Tells Us About Intent

A $16 million operation targeted at a single individual over fourteen months is not a casual harassment campaign. It is not the work of a rogue officer with a grudge. It is not something you do by accident or by improvisation.

A $16 million operation requires: a budget allocation, which requires a budget decision; a budget decision requires institutional authorization; institutional authorization requires a legal or operational justification; a legal justification requires a designation of the target as warranting this level of resource commitment; and a designation requires a decision, by someone with authority, that Richard Pearson — a PhD in public health who advocated for public housing residents and wrote essays about structural racism — was worth $16 million of the federal government's covert operational resources.

Someone made that decision. Someone wrote the justification. Someone approved the budget. Someone managed the contractors. Someone received the reports. Someone reviewed the operation's progress. These are not anonymous processes. Intelligence community operations of this scope have paperwork. They have oversight. They have chain-of-command accountability, however informal or classified.

The $16 million is not just a cost estimate. It is evidence of institutional intent. It is the dollar value of what someone decided Richard Pearson was worth destroying.

And it is being paid, as all such programs are paid, by the citizens of the country it is being deployed against. The taxpayers of the United States funded, at approximately $16 million of their money, a sustained fourteen-month campaign to torture, surveil, psychologically decompose, physically assault, falsely arrest, and drive into statelessness a Black public health scholar in Washington, DC, whose published crime was writing about structural racism.

That is what the bill says.

