## One Final Calculation

Pearson has published over 150 essays. He has built a 294-page primary record. He has filed a UN complaint with specific treaty citations. He has sought asylum on two continents. He has maintained his analytical framework and his epistemic discipline through everything the $16 million bought.

He did all of this with a laptop, a tote bag, one pair of dress pants, and the methodological training of a PhD.

The return on investment for the program — measured against its stated goal of neutralizing a target — is approximately zero.

The return on investment for the documentation — measured against the cost of producing it — is incalculable.

There is no version of this calculation in which the program wins.

That, too, is something the $16 million cannot buy back.

